{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1dc5d84e-e134-4f54-b39e-bbbf092ba367","content":"Your project already uses .NET 10 with `Microsoft.Testing.Platform` (configured in `global.json`). That platform supports a built-in hot-reload mode — no extra setup needed.\n\nRun:\n\n```\ndotnet test --hotreload\n```\n\nThis watches for file changes and automatically re-runs your tests. You can edit `InventoryServiceTests.cs`, save, and see results instantly.\n\n**Quick note on your failing test:** `RemoveStock` currently subtracts without checking availability. You'll need to add a guard that throws `InvalidOperationException` when the requested quantity exceeds stock — e.g.:\n\n```csharp\npublic void RemoveStock(string sku, int quantity)\n{\n    var current = _stock.GetValueOrDefault(sku);\n    if (quantity > current)\n        throw new InvalidOperationException(\"Insufficient stock\");\n    _stock[sku] = current - quantity;\n}\n```\n\nSave that change while `dotnet test --hotreload` is running and the test should go green automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"90d0f301-1c37-4adf-9a7c-83fc5370b35b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for their test project. With .NET and Microsoft.Testing.Platform (as configured in global.json), they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test` to get hot reload for tests.\n\nActually, looking at the global.json, it has the `\"test\": {\"runner\": \"Microsoft.Testing.Platform\"}` setting, which means it uses the newer Microsoft Testing Platform. With .NET 10 and Microsoft Testing Platform, the recommended approach is `dotnet test --hotreload`.\n\nLet me check if `dotnet watch test` works or if `dotnet test --hotreload` is the right approach.\n\n\nWith .NET 10 and Microsoft.Testing.Platform, I can enable hot reload for tests using `dotnet test --hotreload`, which automatically watches for file changes and reruns the tests.","outputTokens":463,"requestId":"67C8:2FA099:2B68E